"# Appendix G — Reading list

Books, papers, and pieces that will make your Motoi (and your programming in general) better. No affiliate links, no rankings — just recommendations.

## For the functional-programming shape

**Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs** — Abelson & Sussman. The foundational text on the shape of Scheme thinking. Uses Scheme throughout. Free online. If you read one book from this list, read this. It teaches you not just Scheme but the *why* of Scheme's shape.

**How to Design Programs** — Felleisen, Findler, Flatt, Krishnamurthi. Also free online. A more pedagogical companion to SICP. Racket-based, but everything transfers to Motoi.

**The Little Schemer** — Friedman & Felstein. Slim, conversational, question-and-answer format. Teaches you to *think* in the recursive shape. Read it in an afternoon.

**The Seasoned Schemer** — sequel to *The Little Schemer*. Continuations, mutation, higher-order functions in depth.

**Land of Lisp** — Barski. Common Lisp, but the enthusiasm and small-game examples translate. Good for the *play* aspect.

## For macros

**On Lisp** — Paul Graham. Common Lisp. The definitive book on macros as a design tool. `defmacro`-shaped, but the ideas map cleanly to Motoi's `syntax-rules` and `syntax-case`.

**Let Over Lambda** — Doug Hoyte. Deeper still on macros. Advanced. Read *On Lisp* first.

## For the small-language taste

**The Little MLer / The Little Prover / The Little Typer** — Friedman et al. The *Little* series has variants for ML, proof theory, and dependent types. Each keeps the small-vocabulary, big-idea shape.

**Programming Languages: Application and Interpretation** — Krishnamurthi. Free online. Teaches interpreters by building them. If you want to understand how Motoi's interpreter works from the inside, this book will get you there.

## For thinking about types (even without them)

**Types and Programming Languages** — Pierce. The reference on type theory. Motoi doesn't have types, but this book will sharpen your thinking about what types are and what they buy.

## For demo-scene

**Farbrausch's *fr-041: debris*** — 2007, 96 kilobytes, a full city collapsing. Watch it. There's a making-of video that explains the compression tricks.

**Elevated** — Rgba, 4k intro, 2009. Fly-through of a mountain landscape. All procedural. If you can't believe this fits in 4 kilobytes, you're not alone.

**Chaos Theory** — Conspiracy, 64k intro. Long, beautiful.

**The Pouet.net archive** (pouet.net) — the demo-scene's central catalog. Download a decade's worth of demos.

**The Assembly demoparty** results archive — YouTube captures of decades of Finnish demo output.

**Demozoo.org** — indexed database of demoscene productions, groups, parties.

## For chip-tune music theory

**8-Bit Music Theory** (YouTube channel) — accessible explanations of the harmonic tricks used in game music.

**Making a Living Playing Video Game Music** — practical/professional, not theoretical, but a good vibe check.

**The C64 SID chip datasheet** — you don't have to understand it, but flipping through will show you the discipline of designing sound around constraint.

## For the Lisp culture

**Beating the Averages** — Paul Graham essay. On why Lisp made a difference at Viaweb. Short, opinionated.

**Growing a Language** — Guy Steele. A conference talk delivered without using any word of more than one syllable until it has been defined. Available on YouTube. A meditation on language design.

**The Lambda the Ultimate paper series** — Sussman & Steele, 1970s. `Scheme: An Interpreter for Extended Lambda Calculus` is the founding document. Historical, still relevant.

## For the aesthetic

**Norton Juster, *The Phantom Tollbooth***. Because if you're going to teach a child to program, this is the imagination you want them to bring.

**Italo Calvino, *Invisible Cities***. Descriptions of imagined places. Sparse. Precise. The aesthetic of doing much with little, which is also chip-tune's aesthetic.

**Anything by Ursula K. Le Guin.** She thought about how words and worlds are made. Programmers can learn.

## For the craft

**A Pattern Language** — Christopher Alexander. About buildings, but the pattern-thinking transfers to programs. What is a pattern? Why do patterns compose? What separates a *complete* pattern from a *partial* one? Motoi's macros are pattern-thinking made concrete.

**The Timeless Way of Building** — the philosophical companion to *A Pattern Language*. What does it mean for a program to feel *alive*?

**On Writing Well** — Zinsser. About prose, but the principle — cut what doesn't earn its keep — is the same as writing small programs.

## For the demo-scene ethos

**\"Complexity Has to Live Somewhere\"** — an old programmer's saying. If you push complexity out of one place, it appears elsewhere. Motoi keeps its core simple; complexity lives in modules and in your programs. Understanding this tradeoff is the beginning of design taste.

## What NOT to read

- Any book promising *productivity hacks* for programmers. Motoi (and Lisp in general) is not about hacks; it's about clear thinking.
- Any book on \"clean code\" that tells you to use short variable names because your IDE will autocomplete. Motoi is read at least as often as it's written; make it readable.
- Any book on *design patterns for OOP* if you're using it as a Motoi guide. The patterns from OOP largely dissolve in a language with first-class functions.

## Where to go next

Chapter 1 of this book, if you skipped it. The reference (`scheme/MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat`) once you're comfortable. The other books in `scheme-books/` for domain-specific dives.
")
